e our computations. If we do parallelize everything, we can have essentially free speedups, which wouldn’t be as possible in imperative programming language","position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1,"offset":971},"end":{"line":36,"column":243,"offset":1213}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":36,"column":1,"offset":971},"end":{"line":36,"column":243,"offset":1213}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, our goal is to have a language that allows us to still reason equationally, but has access to mutability, as side effects are what we use to interact with the outside world (pure programs, while great, can’t do much alone. They NEED interaction to be useful)","position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1,"offset":1215},"end":{"line":38,"column":263,"offset":1477}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":38,"column":1,"offset":1215},"end":{"line":38,"column":263,"offset":1477}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To do so, we can use “Encapsulated Commands”","position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1,"offset":1479},"end":{"line":40,"column":45,"offset":1523}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":40,"column":1,"offset":1479},"end":{"line":40,"column":45,"offset":1523}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"hr","properties":{},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":42,"column":1,"offset":1525},"end":{"line":42,"column":4,"offset":1528}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Encapsulated Commands","position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":5,"offset":1534},"end":{"line":44,"column":26,"offset":1555}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":44,"column":1,"offset":1530},"end":{"line":44,"column":26,"offset":1555}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Like stated in the last set of notes, instead of adding the mutability judgement and complicating our judgement semantics, what we can do is separate the mutable and immutable parts of our language. ","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1,"offset":1557},"end":{"line":46,"column":200,"offset":1756}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1,"offset":1557},"end":{"line":46,"column":200,"offset":1756}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"To do that, we’ll create an expression language, which contains the evaluation judgement we’re all used to and the value judgement. This’ll serve as the base for our functional part of the language, where we can preserve all of this simplicity.","position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1,"offset":1758},"end":{"line":48,"column":245,"offset":2002}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":48,"column":1,"offset":1758},"end":{"line":48,"column":245,"offset":2002}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"We’ll also, however, create a command-oriented language, which serves to take state, command pairs and translate to state command pairs through a similar evaluation judgement. Here is the imperative part of our program, where we can work with memory only when it’s necessary, and even then still reason about the expression language functionally. ","position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1,"offset":2004},"end":{"line":50,"column":348,"offset":2351}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":50,"column":1,"offset":2004},"end":{"line":50,"column":348,"offset":2351}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So, when we execute an impure program, we’ll create a list of commands through the work in our pure language. Then, we’ll simply execute the reads/writes afterwards.","position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1,"offset":2353},"end":{"line":52,"column":166,"offset":2518}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":52,"column":1,"offset":2353},"end":{"line":52,"column":166,"offset":2518}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Evaluate the expressions first to a value, which can be a command, then we execute the command that results from the evaluation (i.e. make the side-effects)","position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1,"offset":2520},"end":{"line":54,"column":157,"offset":2676}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":54,"column":1,"offset":2520},"end":{"line":54,"column":157,"offset":2676}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Let’s see how this works in the real world through the language Haskell’s I/O syntax.","position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1,"offset":2678},"end":{"line":56,"column":86,"offset":2763}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":56,"column":1,"offset":2678},"end":{"line":56,"column":86,"offset":2763}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"hr","properties":{},"children":[],"position":{"start":{"line":58,"column":1,"offset":2765},"end":{"line":58,"column":4,"offset":2768}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"h3","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Haskell I/O","position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":5,"offset":2774},"end":{"line":60,"column":16,"offset":2785}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":60,"column":1,"offset":2770},"end":{"line":60,"column":16,"offset":2785}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Haskell actually uses encapsulated commands through something called the I/O monad. What is a monad?","position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1,"offset":2787},"end":{"line":62,"column":101,"offset":2887}}}],"position":{"start":{"line":62,"column":1,"offset":2787},"end":{"line":62,"column":101,"offset":2887}}},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName